Data Privacy and Security Why it matters: Generative AI models often require large datasets for training or fine-tuning. If employees input proprietary code, sensitive client information, or protected intellectual property into public AI tools, that data may become part of the model‚Äôs permanent training set, leading to data leaks or regulatory non-compliance Algorithmic Fairness and Bias Why it matters: AI models are trained on historical data that may contain societal biases regarding race, gender, or age. If these models are used to assist in hiring, performance reviews, or customer service, they may inadvertently automate and scale discrimination, leading to reputational damage and legal liability. Transparency and Explainability Why it matters: Generative AI often functions as a "black box," making it difficult to understand how it reached a specific conclusion or generated a specific piece of content. In a business context, being unable to explain a decision to a stakeholder or auditor can erode trust and make it difficult to correct errors or "hallucinations."



